00:00:00.109 --> 00:00:01.700 align:undefined
<c.cue-0>Principle of unity. </c>

cue-1
00:00:02.410 --> 00:00:06.280 align:undefined
<c.cue-1>Unity is the idea that people are more likely to be persuaded by those who they </c>

cue-2
00:00:06.289 --> 00:00:10.279 align:undefined
<c.cue-2>perceive as being part of the same group or sharing similar characteristics, </c>

cue-3
00:00:10.289 --> 00:00:11.960 align:undefined
<c.cue-3>identity or even tribe. </c>

cue-4
00:00:12.550 --> 00:00:16.309 align:undefined
<c.cue-4>During a study on a college campus, a young woman solicited </c>

cue-5
00:00:16.319 --> 00:00:19.079 align:undefined
<c.cue-5>donations from people in traffic for a good cause. </c>

cue-6
00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:23.809 align:undefined
<c.cue-6>The study revealed that when she added the statement, "I'm a student here too", </c>

cue-7
00:00:23.819 --> 00:00:27.430 align:undefined
<c.cue-7>prior to making the request, the rate of donations increased by </c>

cue-8
00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:28.729 align:undefined
<c.cue-8>400%. </c>

cue-9
00:00:29.280 --> 00:00:33.229 align:undefined
<c.cue-9>Phishing Attackers can use the principle of unity to create a false </c>

cue-10
00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:35.439 align:undefined
<c.cue-10>sense of shared identity with their target. </c>

cue-11
00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:40.090 align:undefined
<c.cue-11>For example, an attacker may send a phishing email to an employee </c>

cue-12
00:00:40.099 --> 00:00:43.770 align:undefined
<c.cue-12>of a company and pretend to be a member of the same department or team </c>

cue-13
00:00:43.779 --> 00:00:47.090 align:undefined
<c.cue-13>using language and jargon that would be familiar to the employee. </c>

cue-14
00:00:47.720 --> 00:00:51.599 align:undefined
<c.cue-14>This can create a sense of unity and shared identity making the employee </c>

cue-15
00:00:51.610 --> 00:00:55.229 align:undefined
<c.cue-15>more likely to trust the attacker and follow the instructions in the phishing </c>

cue-16
00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:59.240 align:undefined
<c.cue-16>email such as clicking on a link or entering login credentials. </c>